Some good points from other forecasters: @Sjens --> https://www.gjopen.com/comments/comments/72500 "I am forecasting that North Korea will conduct a nuclear test and fire a long range-missile. To keep it consistent (all in;-)): North Korea needs time for that. As a reaction, six party talks would be reasonable and those tests would put North Korea in a strong position. So if North Korea is really planing to test its missiles, it has to be expected that it has no interest in holding talks beforehand. Furthermore, I fear that timing already is a problem for those tests, so I more certainly assume that the talks will not resume before 2017."
~
@sylmarquardt --> https://www.gjopen.com/comments/comments/72450 "Obama will leave it to his successor so that he/she can start with a more hawkish stance."
~
@Anneinak --> https://www.gjopen.com/comments/comments/72428 "Because GJP asked this question last year, I followed it for quite a while, and at no time did resumption of the talks seem possible. Given that I think DRNK is preparing to conduct another nuclear test, I don't think it would be eager to come to the table to talk. I think that the probability is very low, but I'm starting off with a minimally negative forecast until I've done more research and gotten back up to speed on the issue."
~~~~ COMMENT: From what I can tell, two main things to keep in mind that other forecasters have pointed to: 1) NK might be on the cusp of a missile/nuclear test, so why would they come to the table before that, and 2) It might seem odd that Pres. Obama would try to restart these kinds of talks given that they're likely to spill into the next administration. I would add a third point to that -- given the current animosity between Russia and the US, do we really think that they're going to sit down together for talks like these? Especially with what's going on in Europe (Ukraine/Montenegro) and the Middle East (Syria, etc.).
